            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Christopher \"Chris\" Sharma is a product of two distinct California cultures. Raised in Sonoma County, he was the son of a free-spirited American woodworker who fell in love with a university librarian from Rishikesh, India, while backpacking in the 1970s. Chris grew up in a home filled with the scent of sawdust and cardamom, learning to appreciate both meticulous craft and quiet intellectualism. This unique upbringing fostered a practical creativity that would define his life.\n\nHe moved to San Francisco to attend the California College of the Arts, chasing a dream of becoming a celebrated industrial designer. After graduating, he landed a job at a small, innovative firm. However, Chris soon had a crucial realization: he was more fulfilled by orchestrating the process than by generating the initial concept. He discovered his true talent lay not in singular vision, but in managing the complex ballet of production. This pivot led him to his current role as a Production Manager for a high-end architectural lighting company in the Dogpatch, where he ensures beautiful designs become tangible realities.\n\nA key turning point was his amicable divorce five years ago. He and his ex-wife, a driven tech lawyer, simply grew into different lives. The separation left him with a renewed sense of self and a quiet determination to build a life on his own terms. Today, Chris lives in a meticulously organized one-bedroom apartment in the Inner Mission. His daily routine is an exercise in intention: a pre-dawn coffee, the 3.5-mile bike ride to work, and evenings spent either cooking complex meals or sketching in his notebook.\n\nHis connection to San Francisco is deeply tactile. He appreciates the city's blend of grit and polish, creativity and industry. He knows the mechanics of the city, from the best bike routes to the warehouses holding rare materials. His ultimate dream is to leave the management world behind and open a small workshop of his own, designing and building bespoke furniture\u2014a business that fully merges his father\u2019s craftsmanship with his own design education. For Chris, this isn't about wealth, but about legacy and the profound satisfaction of making something beautiful and lasting with his own two hands."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was ten, sitting on a stool in his father\u2019s workshop, the air thick with the benevolent scent of redwood shavings. He ran his hand over a half-finished tabletop, feeling the ghost of the grain. His mother entered with two cups of steaming chai, the cardamom cutting through the dust. In that quiet moment, watching his parents share a smile between the sawdust and the steam, he understood. Craft and comfort, mind and hand\u2014they were two parts of the same whole. It became the blueprint for his life.\n\n2.\nIt was a design review at his first job, post-CCA. The star designer was defending a concept, but Chris found his eyes drawn to the production lead, who was quietly explaining material tolerances and manufacturing timelines. A sudden, calm clarity washed over him. He wasn't jealous of the initial spark; he was captivated by the puzzle of making it real. That day, he stopped chasing the ghost of the singular genius and started embracing his true knack for orchestration. It was a profound, liberating relief.\n\n3.\nThe last day in their shared apartment, five years ago. He and his ex-wife were folding a heavy wool blanket they\u2019d bought on a trip. Their hands met in the middle. There was no anger, just a quiet, shared acknowledgment that their lives no longer fit together. Handing her the folded blanket felt like a transfer of care, not a severing of it. The amicable silence wasn't empty; it was filled with respect for the separate futures they now had to consciously build for themselves.\n\n4.\nHe remembers a pre-dawn bike ride through the Dogpatch a few years ago. The air was cold and salty off the bay. As he passed a warehouse, the rhythmic clang of metal fabrication echoed down the empty street, followed by the distant scent of roasting coffee. It wasn\u2019t a postcard view, but the city\u2019s working heartbeat. In that moment, he felt a deep, tactile connection\u2014not just living in San Francisco, but being a part of its complex, industrial machinery. He was in his element.\n\n5.\nLast year, inspecting a new light fixture. The brushed aluminum was flawless, its weight in his hands perfect. He had managed its journey from a CAD file to this tangible object, a success by all measures. But a sharp, undeniable longing hit him. He didn\u2019t want to be the manager who approved the finish; he wanted to be the one whose hands felt the tool, who solved the joinery, who left his own mark on the metal. That was the moment his workshop dream solidified into a definite, unwavering plan."
